PANAMA DISEASE, BANANA - INDIA: (TAMIL NADU), NEW STRAIN
********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: December 2010
Source: Down To Earth [edited]
<http://www.downtoearth.org.in/node/2411>


India gets ready for banana war
-------------------------------
A fungus that threatens popular Cavendish bananas
was traced in the country. Just as India was
gearing up to broaden its export base,
researchers have sounded alert: the fungus
_Fusarium oxysporum_ f.sp. _cubense_ is affecting
Cavendish bananas in the country.

Banana growers in the Cumbum region of Tamil Nadu
had been complaining of sporadic occurrences of
the wilt disease for 4 years, said R Thangavelu,
National Research Centre for Banana [NRCB].
Researchers recently surveyed the plantations and
found _F. oxysporum_ is infecting the Cavendish.
M M Mustaffa, director of NRCB, said since the
infection was spotted in a small area it is
unlikely to affect India's Cavendish yield immediately.

C Mohan, Punjab Agricultural University, said it
is difficult to contain the disease once it
breaks out. R K Jain, Indian Agricultural
Research Institute, said the fungus, resistant to
fungicides, can spread through irrigation water.
Any infection capable of killing one banana plant
can wipe out the entire variety because banana lacks genetic diversity.

Thangavelu tested the virulence of the fungus
from Cumbum on a Cavendish variety, Grand Naine,
and indigenous varieties. Red Banana and Nendran
[varieties] did not get infected, he said.
Farmers should be encouraged to cultivate
Cavendish bananas and rice alternately, plant
fungus-resistant varieties and should buy
uninfected corm from reliable sources or adopt tissue culture.

[Byline: Anirudh Nair]

